on musical structure, identifying elements and processes that give the music coherence, character, and interest. Skoumal demonstrates how the music combines and blends traditional tonal elements, folk-influenced features, and techniques that were forward-looking at the time. In particular, the music is shown to employ highly sophisticated and continually transforming motivic and rhythmic components. The book's numerous musical analyses are motivically centered and employ various analytical approaches, including ones that involve reduction, structural levels, basic set theory, and rhythmic theory. Discussions of Janácek's works with a libretto or other type of text consider relationships between word and music, revealing their connection to deeper structural issues. The companion website https://zdenekskoumal.wixsite.com/janacek features audio versions of most musical examples, as well as material not included in the book.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMusicxAnalysis, appreciationy19th century. 0aMusicxAnalysis, appreciationy20th century. 4aMusic. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aLeos Janácek.  acomposition.  afolk-influenced features.  aforward-looking techniques.  amotivic structure.  amusic analysis.  amusic coherence.  amusic theory.  amusical language.  arhythmic structure.  atonal elements.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311143101740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787449176?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787449176423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787449176/original  a978-3-11-143101-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles